'''Jim Hague''' (born James Frederick Hague, June 2, 1961 in [[Jersey City, New Jersey]]) is a long-time sportswriter in northern New Jersey as well as a public address announcer for [[Rutgers University]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Jim Hague|url=http://www.rutgersnewarkathletics.com/staff.aspx?staff=15|work=rutgersnewarkathletics.com|publisher=Rutgers University|accessdate=19 January 2011}}</ref> and local high schools.

==Early career==
Hague is a [[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City]] native who attended [[St. Peter's Preparatory School]] (Class of 1979) and [[Marquette University]] before becoming a sportswriter in 1983, when he took his first professional job with the Morristown ''[[Daily Record (Morristown)|Daily Record]]''.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}

Before signing on with the ''Daily Record'', Hague was the public relations director and public address announcer for the [[Jersey Indians]], a Class AA located in his hometown of Jersey City, in the summer of 1978, where he watched future Hall of Famer [[Rickey Henderson]] play on a daily basis.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}

He remained at the ''Daily Record'' through 1985, then had short stints with the ''North Jersey Advance'' in Dover and the ''Woodbridge News-Tribune'', both papers that have since closed.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}

==''Hudson Dispatch''==
In September 1986, Hague joined the staff of the ''[[Hudson Dispatch]]'' in [[Union City, New Jersey]]. where he remained until that paper's demise in April 1991. During his stint at the ''Hudson Dispatch'', eventually becoming one of the paper's most known sports columnists, Hague won several [[New Jersey Press Association]] and [[North Jersey Press Club]] awards. Hague also became known for his coverage of the [[Meadowlands Grand Prix]], the Indy car race held in the parking lot of the [[Meadowlands Sports Complex]], and was recognized nationally for his coverage.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}

In 1991, Hague became the first-ever sports columnist for the ''Hudson Reporter'' newspaper chain, where he has also garnered several awards. He remains with the newspaper chain today. He also currently writes a sports column for The Observer of Kearny, where he has written since 2002. Hague is also a stringer for the Associated Press, covering [[Seton Hall]] basketball and [[New York Red Bulls]] soccer among his assignments.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}

During his career, Hague has also worked as the Sports Information Director at [[Saint Peter's University|St. Peter's College]] in Jersey City (1986–1990) and has done several different radio and television appearances.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}

==''Star-Ledger''==
Hague spent 12 years working for Dorf Feature Services, providing stories for ''[[The Star-Ledger]]'' of Newark. During his days there, Hague covered the [[New York Knicks]] and [[New Jersey Nets]], compiled the information for the Ledger's High School Football Team of the Century (1999) and covered a variety of sports.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}

==Current career==
In 2005, Hague's first book, ''Braddock: The Rise of the Cinderella Man'', was published by Chamberlain Brothers, a subsidiary of Penguin Books. The book, written about former heavyweight boxing champion [[James J. Braddock]], was published in England and in Italy and appeared on the best seller list in Italy in August that year.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}

In 2007, Hague returned to his roots as he returned to the ''Daily Record'', covering high school football, cross country, indoor track, hockey and golf.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}

Since 2004, Hague has been the public address announcer for both Rutgers-Newark and [[New Jersey Institute of Technology]] sporting events. Hague also writes a weekly Athlete of the Week feature for the Rutgers-Newark athletic website.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}

