A '''marriage market''' can refer to a public place where parents list advertisements for their children with the aim of finding a [[marriage|marital]] [[spouse]] for them.<ref name="Larmer">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/10/business/in-a-changing-china-new-matchmaking-markets.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 | title=The Price of Marriage in China | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=March 9, 2013 | accessdate=May 13, 2013 | author=Larmer, Brook}}</ref> People then congregate there and read the listings, often in the hope of finding a marital match.<ref name="Tacon"/> Several marriage markets exist in [[China]], such as [[Shanghai marriage market|Shanghai's marriage market]] at [[People's Square (Shanghai)|People's Square]]<ref name="Tacon">{{cite web | url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/inpictures/2013/04/201343113125739211.html | title=Finding a spouse in a Chinese marriage market | publisher=Al Jazeera | date=April 6, 2013 | accessdate=May 13, 2013 | author=Tacon, Dave}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Warner|first=David|title=Shanghai's marriage market: Bridal bliss or marital mayhem?|url=http://www.cnngo.com/shanghai/play/sausage-fest-2020-future-shanghai-marriage-market-086672 |accessdate=May 13, 2013|newspaper=CNN Travel|date= February 11, 2010}}</ref> and at several parks and other public places in [[Beijing]], such as shopping malls.<ref name="Larmer"/>
[[File:Finding a Match is easier than finding a Parking Space, Chennai.jpg|thumb|300px|Finding a Match is easier than finding a Parking Space, [[Chennai]], India]]

A marriage market can also refer to the use of marriage [[broker]]s<ref name="Trivedi"/> and marriage bureaus<ref>{{cite web | url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-09-23/pune/34039993_1_marriage-bureau-stay-at-home-status-work-timings | title=Stay-at-home brides rule marriage market | publisher=''The Times of India'' | date=September 23, 2012 | accessdate=2013-05-13}}</ref> that are involved in [[matchmaking]] to unite people in marriage.<ref name="Trivedi">{{cite web | url=http://india.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/01/15/in-delhi-women-marry-up-and-men-are-left-behind/ | title=In New Delhi, Women Marry Up and Men Are Left Behind | publisher=''The New York Times'' | date=January 15, 2013 | accessdate=2013-05-13 | author=Trivedi, Anjani}}</ref> In October 2011, marriage markets in [[India]] involving the use of brokers was estimated to be a $250 billion ([[Indian Rupee]]) industry.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Luxury/The-new-business-of-marriage/Article1-762156.aspx | title=The (new) business of marriage | publisher=Hindustan Times | date=October 28, 2011 | accessdate=2013-05-13 | author=Trivedi, Ira | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130516053001/http://www.hindustantimes.com/Entertainment/Luxury/The-new-business-of-marriage/Article1-762156.aspx | archivedate=May 16, 2013 | df= }}</ref> Marriage markets using brokers exists in [[New Delhi]], India<ref name="Trivedi"/> and in several other regions of India.

