{{Infobox book | name = The Protest Psychosis: How Schizophrenia Became a Black Disease | image = The Protest Psychosis (book cover).jpg | author = [[Jonathan Metzl]] | country = United States | subject = [[Psychiatry]] | publisher = [[Beacon Press]] | pub_date = 2010 | media_type = Print | pages = 246 | isbn = 0-8070-8592-8 | oclc = 319496892 | italic title = force }}
'''''The Protest Psychosis: How Schizophrenia Became a Black Disease''''' is a 2010 book by the [[psychiatrist]] [[Jonathan Metzl]] (who also has a Ph.D. in [[American studies]]), and published by [[Beacon Press]],<ref name="Metzl">{{cite book|last=Metzl|first=Jonathan|title=The Protest Psychosis: How Schizophrenia Became a Black Disease|year=2010|publisher=[[Beacon Press]]|isbn=0-8070-8592-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t1Bg9QEiCAMC&printsec=frontcover}}</ref> covering the history of the 1960s [[Ionia State Hospital]]&mdash;located in [[Ionia, Michigan]] and converted into the [[Ionia Correctional Facility]] in 1986. The facility is claimed to have been one of America's largest and most notorious state [[psychiatric hospital]]s in the era before [[deinstitutionalization]].
Metzl focuses on exposing the trend of this hospital to diagnose [[African American]]s with [[schizophrenia]] because of their [[civil rights]] ideas. He suggests that in part the sudden influx of such diagnoses could be traced to a change in wording in the [[DSM-II]], which compared to the previous edition added "hostility" and "aggression" as signs of the disorder. Metzl writes that this change resulted in [[institutional racism|structural racism]]. [[File:Haldol advertisement from 1974 Archives of General Psychiatry.jpg|278px|thumbnail|A 1974 ad for the drug [[Haldol]] published in the medical journal ''[[Archives of General Psychiatry]]'', and reproduced in ''The Protest Psychosis''. Author Metzl states that the advertisement shows an attempt to equate racial unrest with mental illness.]] The book was well reviewed in ''[[JAMA (journal)|JAMA]]'', where it was described as "a fascinating, penetrating book by one of medicine's most exceptional young scholars."<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Wear | first1 = D. | title = The Protest Psychosis: How Schizophrenia Became a Black Disease | doi = 10.1001/jama.2010.629 | journal = [[JAMA: the Journal of the American Medical Association]] | volume = 303 | issue = 19 | pages = 1984–1984 | year = 2010 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> The book was also reviewed in the ''[[American Journal of Psychiatry]]'',<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Luhrmann | first1 = T. M. | title = The Protest Psychosis: How Schizophrenia Became a Black Disease | doi = 10.1176/appi.ajp.2009.09101398 | journal = [[American Journal of Psychiatry]] | volume = 167 | issue = 4 | pages = 479–480 | year = 2010 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> ''[[Psychiatric Services]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Bell, Carl|title=The Protest Psychosis: How Schizophrenia Became a Black Disease|journal=[[Psychiatric Services]]|date=1 August 2011|volume=62|issue=8|pages=979–980|doi=10.1176/appi.ps.62.8.979-a}}</ref> ''[[Transcultural Psychiatry]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|author1=McKenzie, Kwame|title=Jonathan M. Metzl, The Protest Psychosis: How Schizophrenia Became a Black Disease|journal=[[Transcultural Psychiatry]]|date=July–September 2012|volume=49|issue=3–4|pages=640–642|doi=10.1177/1363461512448783}}</ref> ''[[Psychiatric Times]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Fernando, Suman|title=Review – The Protest Psychosis: How Schizophrenia Became a Black Disease|journal=[[Psychiatric Times]]|date=21 October 2010|url=http://www.psychiatrictimes.com/film-and-book-reviews/review-%E2%80%93-protest-psychosis-how-schizophrenia-became-black-disease}}</ref> ''[[The American Journal of Bioethics]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Aultman, Julie|title=Review of Jonathan Metzl, The Protest Psychosis: How Schizophrenia Became a Black Disease|journal=[[The American Journal of Bioethics]]|date=2010|volume=10|issue=11|pages=37–38|doi=10.1080/15265161.2010.520600}}</ref> ''[[Social History of Medicine]]'',<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Wald | first1 = P. | doi = 10.1093/shm/hkr027 | title = Jonathan M. Metzl, the Protest Psychosis: How Schizophrenia Became a Black Disease | journal = [[Social History of Medicine]] | volume = 24 | pages = 194–195 | year = 2011 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> ''[[Medical Anthropology Quarterly]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|author=Freidenberg, Judith|title=The Protest Psychosis: How Schizophrenia Became a Black Disease by Jonathan Metzl|journal=[[Medical Anthropology Quarterly]]|date=June 2012|volume=26|issue=2|pages=309–310|doi=10.1111/j.1548-1387.2012.01214.x}}</ref> ''[[Journal of African American History]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|author=Johnson, Frank|title=The Protest Psychosis: How Schizophrenia Became a Black Disease by Jonathan M. Metzl|journal=[[Journal of African American History]]|date=Fall 2012|volume=97|issue=4|pages=499–501|doi=10.5323/jafriamerhist.97.4.0499}}</ref> ''[[Journal of Black Psychology]]'',<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Sherry, Alissa|title=Book Review: Metzl, J. M. (2010). The Protest Psychosis: How Schizophrenia Became a Black Disease|journal=[[Journal of Black Psychology]]|date=August 2011|volume=37|issue=3|pages=381–383|doi=10.1177/0095798411407066}}</ref> ''[[Health: An Interdisciplinary Journal for the Social Study of Health, Illness and Medicine]]'',<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Schneider | first1 = B. | title = Book review: J.M. Metzl, the Protest Psychosis: How Schizophrenia Became a Black Disease, Beacon Press: Boston, MA, 2010; 246 pp | doi = 10.1177/13634593110150020605 | journal = [[Health (journal)|Health: An Interdisciplinary Journal for the Social Study of Health, Illness and Medicine]] | volume = 15 | issue = 2 | pages = 213–214 | year = 2011 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> ''The Sixties: A Journal of History, Politics and Culture''.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Staub, Michael|title=The protest psychosis: how schizophrenia became a black disease|journal=The Sixties: A Journal of History, Politics and Culture|date=2010|volume=3|issue=2|pages=253–255|doi=10.1080/17541328.2010.525948}}</ref>
